<Base title="About — MemoryHole">
  <h1>Methodology</h1>
  <p>
    MemoryHole is an autonomous observatory for <strong>silent edits</strong>: changes made
    to published news articles and official statements after publication, without any
    correction notice. Once a day it re-reads every tracked page and records what changed.
  </p>

  <h2>How detection works</h2>
  <p>
    Article URLs are discovered from RSS feeds (plus a list of static pages) and each
    article's readable text is extracted with trafilatura, aggressively normalized —
    whitespace, unicode, quotes, boilerplate, timestamps — so that cosmetic HTML churn
    never registers as an edit. Each page's normalized text is snapshotted in git; git
    history is the archive. New text is diffed word-by-word against the previous snapshot.
  </p>

  <h2>Severity classification</h2>
  <p>Each detected edit is scored by combining rule-based signals — numbers changed,
    named entities swapped, quotes deleted, paragraphs added or removed, headline
    changes — with semantic similarity from a local sentence-transformers model
    (all-MiniLM-L6-v2). No external API is required.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><span class="badge COSMETIC">COSMETIC</span> — typos, punctuation, formatting; meaning identical.</li>
    <li><span class="badge MINOR">MINOR</span> — rewording with the same meaning.</li>
    <li><span class="badge FACTUAL">FACTUAL</span> — numbers, names or dates changed.</li>
    <li><span class="badge NARRATIVE">NARRATIVE</span> — claims added or removed, headline changed, meaning shifted.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Classification is heuristic. A <em>FACTUAL</em> or <em>NARRATIVE</em> badge means the
    text changed in a way worth a human look — it does not by itself imply bad faith.
    Outlets legitimately update developing stories; the point is that the record of change
    should be public.
  </p>

  <h2>Ethics</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>robots.txt is respected; the crawler identifies itself honestly as
      <code>MemoryHoleBot/1.0</code> and fetches at most one page per two seconds per domain.</li>
    <li>Paywalled content is never fetched or stored.</li>
    <li>Only extracted article text needed for diffing is stored, always with attribution
      and a link to the original.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Run your own</h2>
  <p>
    MemoryHole is MIT-licensed and runs entirely on free infrastructure (GitHub Actions +
    Pages). Fork it, edit <code>sources.yaml</code>, enable Pages — done.
    <a href="https://github.com/dipeshrayg/memoryhole">Source and instructions on GitHub.</a>
  </p>
</Base>
